# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Start making the value 1 from the first index of the array and if the value is 0 means we have to flip the value to 1 and consequently we have to flip next K-1 values as well.

But instead of flipping next K-1 value as well, we will keep a counter which says how many times the values need to alter because of previous operation and mark the (i+k)th index of the reset vector to -1.

**For ex:** 
Input: nums = [0,0,0,1,0,1,1,0], k = 3
Take a reset vector [0,0,0,0,0,0,0,0] and a counter  = 0

**For every values from 0th index to (N-k)th index:**

**At nums[0],** we need to flip the nums[0], so we increase the counter by 1 and mark the (0+3)th index of reset vector as -1
**nums is [1,0,0,1,0,1,1,0]
reset vector is [0,0,0,-1,0,0,0,0] and counter  = 1**

**At nums[1],** the values is '0' but the counter variable says we need to flip the nums[1] one times, so you can observe that it will eventually become '1'. Hence, nothing to do.
**nums is [1,0,0,1,0,1,1,0]
reset vector is [0,0,0,-1,0,0,0,0] and counter  = 1**

**At nums[2],** the values is '0' but the counter variable says we need to flip the nums[2] one times, so you can observe that it will eventually become '1'. Hence, nothing to do.
**nums is [1,1,1,1,0,1,1,0]
reset vector is [0,0,0,-1,0,0,0,0] and counter  = 1**

**At nums[3],** we need to **pay attention**, reset vector at this position is -1, that ,means we have to reduce the effect of one of the operation that had made earlier. Hence , count value gets updated to count = count + rest[3] = 1 + (-1) = 0. Hence no flips made to nums[3]
Now, the values at nums[3] is '1' so no operation is required.
**nums is [1,1,1,1,0,1,1,0]
reset vector is [0,0,0,-1,0,0,0,0] and counter  = 1**


**At nums[4],** the counter variable remains '0' as counter  + reset[4] = 0 + 0 = 0.
But the values at nums[4] is '1'. Hence we need to perform one operation of K-flip again. So,we increase the counter by 1 and mark the (4+3)th index of reset vector as -1.
**nums is [1,1,1,1,1,1,1,0]
reset vector is [0,0,0,-1,0,0,0,-1] and counter  = 1**

**At nums[5],** the counter variable is updated as counter  + reset[5] = 1 + 0 = 1.
and the values at nums[5] is '1' and we need to flip the value one time, so value becomes '0'.
Hence we need to perform one operation of K-flip again. So,we increase the counter by 1 and mark the (5+3)th index of reset vector as -1. 
**The reset vector index goes out of bound so we can ignore, but its a valid K-flip.**
**nums is [1,1,1,1,1,1,1,0]
reset vector is [0,0,0,-1,0,0,0,-1] and counter  = 2**

**At nums[6],** the counter variable is updated as counter  + reset[6] = 2 + 0 = 2.
and the values at nums[6] is '1' and we need to flip the value two times, so no change in value and it is still '1'.
Hence we don'tneed to perform oany operation of K-flip again.
**nums is [1,1,1,1,1,1,1,0]
reset vector is [0,0,0,-1,0,0,0,-1] and counter  = 2**

**At nums[7],** the counter variable is updated as counter  + reset[7] = 2 + -1 = 1.
and the values at nums[7] is '0' and we need to flip the value one time, so value becomes '1'.
Hence we need to perform any K-flip operation.
**nums is [1,1,1,1,1,1,1,1]
reset vector is [0,0,0,-1,0,0,0,-1] and counter  = 1
**

If you have understood the above implementation you will observe that 
if counter values is **even** means we don't have to flip the value
if its **odd** we have to flip the value
**So I have taken flag instead of counter variable and same did with the reset vector.**

Please refer the code.


# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(N)

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(N)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minKBitFlips(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        int ans = 0;

        int i = 0, j = 0;
        int n = nums.size();
        vector<int> reset(n,0);

        int flag = 1;
        while(i<=(n-k)){
            flag = flag^reset[i];
            if(nums[i]^flag){
                ans++;
                if(i+k<n){
                    reset[i+k] = 1;
                }
                flag = !flag;
            }
            i++;
        }

        while(i<n){
            flag = flag^reset[i];
            if(nums[i]^flag){
                return -1;
            }
            i++;
        }

        return ans;
    }
};
```

