solutions.content:
Consider any ith bit, we put a k-sized sliding window so that the ith bit is at the back of the window.
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/7968954d-4298-4db1-9b0b-3b4320ea147e_1651751229.2535677.png)

All the flips happen in this window will be accountable for flipping the ith bit.
We could store a flag, namely flipped, such that it will accumulate all the flips.
When i < k, this flag will be reflecting all the flips done within the sliding windows.
Starting from i = k, one bit will be taken out from this sliding window when we move along, and therefore we need to negate the flip triggered by the (i-k)th bit.
In order to know whether the (i-k)th bit is triggering a flip in linear time, we could use a boolean array to help, and set it the true when any ith bit is tiggerring a flip.
Once we know whether the ith bit is flipped by the preceeding bits in the sliding window, we could match it with the value to see if we need to trigger a flip.
When i > len - k, no flipping is allowed, so we could return -1 if a flip is needed.

Time complexity: O(n)
We loopped n times and each iteration is linear time

Space complexity: O(n)
The boolean array is n-sized
**notes: we could eliminate the use of the boolean array with the given int array to make it O(1), consider we have 32 bits per element and only the least significant bit is currently occupied*

```
class Solution {
    public int minKBitFlips(int[] nums, int k) {
        int len = nums.length, count = 0;
        boolean[] flip = new boolean[len];
        boolean flipped = false;
        for (int i = 0; i < len; i++) {
            if (i >= k && flip[i - k]) flipped = !flipped;
            if ((flipped?1:0) == nums[i]){
                if (i + k > len) return -1;
                count++;
                flip[i] = true;
                flipped = !flipped;
            }
        }
        return count;
    }
}
```

