solutions.content:
Make a `queue ` that will keep track of the first indices of  `k`-bitflips from left to right.
These first indices of `k`-bitflips must be in the range `[0, nums.size() - k ]`.

For index `i`, if we flipped `n` bits out of  range `[i - k + 1, i - 1]` , the bit at `i` is now `nums[i] + n` modulo 2.

If `nums[i] + n` is even, the bit at index `i` is `0`, so flip `k`-bits starting at index`i`. (i,e `push` `i` to the `queue`.) 
if  `nums[i] + n` is odd, the bit at index `i` is `1`. So don't` push` `i` to the queue.



**Algorithm: **

1. if the `front `of the `queue` is more than `k` distance away from index `i`, pop it.
2. count the size of the queue. (this determines how many flips were made on the bit at index `i`.)
3. if `i` is not one of the very last `k - 1` indices and `nums[i] + q.size()` is an even number, push index `i` to the queue (we flip the bit at index `i`)
4. if `i` is one of the very last `k - 1` indices and `nums[i] + q.size()` is an even number, return `-1`.
5. Return the total number of `push` operations. (# of flips)



```
class Solution {
public:
    int minKBitFlips(vector<int>& nums, int k) {

        int count = 0;

        queue<int> q;
        for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {

            if (!q.empty() && i - q.front() >= k) {
                q.pop();
            }

            if (i <= nums.size() - k) {

                if ((nums[i] + q.size()) % 2 == 0) {
                    q.push(i);
                    count++;
                } 

            } else {
                if ((nums[i] + q.size()) % 2 != 1) return -1;
            }

        }  

        return count;
    }
};
```

